# ADR-004: Referral Attribution Model

## Status

Accepted

## Date

2026-06-28

## Context

Relationship-driven commerce depends on trust, word of mouth, recommendations, referrals, and community participation.

Famm should eventually support referrals between:

- Clients and trainers
- Clients and other clients
- Trainers and clients
- Businesses and trainers
- Affiliates and customers
- Communities and members

The broader platform must support referral attribution across many industries, not only fitness.

Examples include:

- A client referring a friend to a trainer
- A student referring another student to a tutor
- A customer referring someone to a tattoo artist
- A therapist receiving a referral from a professional partner
- A creator rewarding an affiliate
- A community driving a purchase
- A coach rewarding ambassadors

Referral behavior should not be treated as a marketing afterthought. It should be a first-class platform capability.

## Decision

The platform will model referrals as first-class platform objects and domain events.

Referral attribution must track:

- Referrer
- Referred party
- Target entity
- Attribution source
- Conversion event
- Reward or compensation status
- Associated transaction, when applicable
- Associated offer, when applicable
- Associated organization or tenant

The platform will support both informal referrals and formal affiliate-style attribution.

## Layer

Platform Core

## Platform Primitives Affected

- User
- Organization
- Relationship
- Offer
- Transaction
- Referral
- Affiliate
- Event
- ReputationSignal

## Proposed Referral Model

The platform referral model should support:

```text
referral_id
organization_id or tenant_id
referrer_entity_id
referrer_entity_type
referred_entity_id
referred_entity_type
target_entity_id
target_entity_type
offer_id
transaction_id
status
source
created_at
converted_at
rewarded_at
metadata
```

Example referral statuses:

```text
created
clicked
claimed
converted
rewarded
expired
cancelled
```

Example referral events:

```text
referral.created
referral.clicked
referral.claimed
referral.converted
referral.rewarded
```

## Alternatives Considered

### Alternative 1: Do Not Track Referrals in V1

This would simplify the MVP, but it would weaken the long-term platform strategy.

Rejected because referrals are core to relationship-commerce.

### Alternative 2: Use UTM Parameters Only

UTM tracking can help marketing attribution, but it does not create a platform-native referral graph.

Rejected because the platform needs to understand who referred whom, what converted, and what value was created.

### Alternative 3: First-Class Referral Primitive

Accepted because referrals should become part of the platform graph, commerce model, reputation system, and future marketplace.

## Consequences

### Positive Consequences

- Supports viral growth loops.
- Supports creator-style economics.
- Supports affiliate programs.
- Supports community-driven commerce.
- Supports word-of-mouth attribution.
- Supports future recommendation systems.
- Strengthens the platform’s relationship graph.

### Negative Consequences

- Requires careful fraud prevention.
- Requires attribution rules.
- Requires reward logic.
- Requires privacy-aware design.
- Requires clear event tracking.

## Cross-Industry Impact

This model supports referrals for:

- Trainers
- Therapists
- Tutors
- Music teachers
- Tattoo artists
- Coaches
- Consultants
- Creators
- Community leaders

Every relationship-driven industry benefits from trusted introductions and attribution.

## Scale Impact

### 1,000 Active Users

Referral tracking can begin with simple referral links and manual reward logic.

### 10,000 Active Users

The platform can support automated attribution, referral dashboards, and basic rewards.

### 100,000 Active Users

Referral data becomes a major strategic asset for growth, recommendations, ranking, and marketplace dynamics.

### Multiple Vertical Applications

The same referral system can power different vertical applications without being rewritten.

### Third-Party Developers

Developers can integrate referral creation, attribution, and conversion APIs into their own applications.

## AI Review Summary

AI coding tools must not implement referrals as simple marketing fields or one-off tracking parameters when the behavior affects platform relationships, transactions, or rewards.

When a feature includes recommendations, invitations, affiliate links, ambassador rewards, or word-of-mouth conversion, AI tools must evaluate whether it belongs in the `Referral` or `Affiliate` platform model.

## Final Decision

Accepted.

Referrals will be modeled as first-class platform primitives and domain events. Referral attribution will become part of the platform’s relationship-commerce graph.
